            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;In CS theory, regular languages &lt;i&gt;are&lt;/i&gt; a strict subset of context-free languages, but regular expression implementations in mainstream programming languages are more powerful.  As &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.noulakaz.net/weblog/2007/03/18/a-regular-expression-to-check-for-prime-numbers/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer&quot;&gt;noulakaz.net/weblog/2007/03/18/&lt;/a&gt; describes, so-called &quot;regular expressions&quot; can check for prime numbers in unary, which is certainly something that a regular expression from CS theory can&apos;t accomplish.&lt;/span&gt;

